-- S2 INVERSION (2026-07-14) — the headline bug, pinned in a BUILT BINARY.
--
-- Was `definer_shadow_dispatch.mdk`, which pinned the OLD rule: a definer shadow applied
-- to a receiver whose head had a live impl DISPATCHED to that impl (`size (Box 3)` -> 3).
-- That rule silently ERASED the user's function whenever the prelude happened to have an
-- impl for the argument's type -- and the prelude has one for almost everything.  That
-- cell is now a located REJECT (see d2 in test/diff_compiler_shadow_semantics.sh), which
-- a build-and-diff-stdout gate cannot express, so this fixture now pins the INVERSION
-- itself: the standalone wins, and the escape hatch still works.
--
-- Line 1: the user's `eq` beats the PRELUDE's `impl Eq List`.  Printed False before.
-- Line 2: `==` still reaches `Eq.eq` -- operators desugar through the method-call path
--         and never touch the bare-name funDef intersection, so they are the one escape
--         hatch that survives inside a shadowing module (SHADOW-SEMANTICS.md 5.3).
eq : List Int -> List Int -> Bool
eq a b = True

main =
  println (debug (eq [1] [2]))
  println (debug ([1] == [2]))
